# Olecranon

> The **olecranon** is the large posterior bony projection at the proximal end of the [[Ulna]] that forms the point of the elbow. It fits into the **olecranon fossa** of the [[Humerus]] during full elbow extension and is the insertion of the [[Triceps Brachii]].

## 🔗 Key Connections
- [[Ulna]] — proximal posterior ulna
- [[Humerus]] — articulates in the olecranon fossa (full extension)
- [[Triceps Brachii]] — inserts on the olecranon (elbow extension)
- [[Ulnar Nerve]] — passes in the cubital tunnel just medial to the olecranon

## 🗂️ Key Facts
| Property | Detail |
|----------|--------|
| Function | Forms elbow point; locks into olecranon fossa in extension |
| Muscle insertion | Triceps brachii |
| Palpation | Prominent bony point of elbow |
| Olecranon bursa | Superficial bursa overlies the olecranon |

## 🏥 Clinical Significance
- **Olecranon fracture** — Usually direct blow or fall on outstretched hand; gap palpable; triceps avulsion
- **Olecranon bursitis (student's elbow)** — Inflamed bursa; soft, fluctuant swelling at elbow point
- **Triceps tendon rupture** — Rare; inability to extend elbow; often at olecranon insertion

